 singles only\n|-\n| \"I Need Somebody Bad\"\n| align=\"center\"| 11\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| 3\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1974\n| \"It's Time to Cross That Bridge\"\n| align=\"center\"| 13\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| 77\n|-\n| \"Sing for the Good Times\"\n| align=\"center\"| 66\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1975\n| \"This Time the Hurtin's On Me\"\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n| \"On the Way Home\"\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n| \"He Little Thing'd Her Out of My Arms\"\n| align=\"center\"| 88\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n| 1976\n| \"Birmingham\"\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1980\n| \"Yours for the Taking\"\n| align=\"center\"| 28\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| rowspan=\"3\"| ''Yours for the Taking''\n|-\n| \"The Rock I'm Leaning On\"\n| align=\"center\"| 48\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n| \"Devil's Den\"\n| align=\"center\"| 63\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1983\n| \"The Jukebox Never Plays Home Sweet Home\"\n| align=\"center\"| 98\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| rowspan=\"7\"| singles only\n|-\n| \"From Cotton to Satin\"\n| align=\"center\"| 92\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n| \"Midnight Tennessee Woman\"\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1984\n| \"I'd Do as Much for You\"\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n| \"Dying to Believe\"\n| align=\"center\"| 93\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n| \"If It's Love (Then Bet It All)\"\n| align=\"center\"| 81\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|-\n| 1985\n| \"Looking Back Is Easier\"\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n| align=\"center\"| \u2014\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1112960/?ref_=fn_al_nm_1 Profile], imdb.com; accessed March 31, 2015. \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060313202449/http://www.opry.com/MeetTheOpry/Members.aspx?id=71 Profile], Grand Ole Opry; accessed March 31, 2015. \n* {{Find a Grave|106731508}}\n\n{{Jack Greene}}\n{{Jeannie Seely}}\n{{CMA Male Vocalist of the Year}}\n{{Grand Ole Opry members}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Greene, Jack}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Maryville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Grand Ole Opry members]]\n[[Category:Deaths from Alzheimer's disease]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Tennessee]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the American historian|Jack P. Greene|those of a similar name|Jack Green (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = Jack Greene\n| image           = Jack Greene.JPG\n| caption         = Jack Greene\n| image_size      = \n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_name      = Jack Henry Greene\n| alias           = \"The Gentle Giant\"<br>\"The Jolly Greene Giant\"\n| birth_date      = {{birth date|1930|01|07|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place     = [[Maryville, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| death_date      = {{death date and age|2013|03|14|1930|01|07|mf=yes}}\n| death_place     = [[Nashville, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| instrument      = [[Guitar]]\n| genre           = [[Country music|Country]]\n| occupation      = [[Singer-songwriter]]\n| years_active    = 1965\u20132011\n| associated_acts = [[Ernest Tubb]]<br> [[Jeannie Seely]]\n| website         = [http://www.jackgreeneopry.com Official website]}}\n\n'''Jack Henry Greene'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Jack-Greene/e/B000APWMLK|title=Jack Greene Amazon.com Bio|publisher=Amazon.com website|year=2013|accessdate=March 16, 2013}}</ref> (January 7, 1930 &ndash; March 14, 2013) was an [[Americans|American]] [[country music|country]] [[musician]]. Nicknamed the \"Jolly Greene Giant\" due to his height and deep voice, Greene was a long time member of the [[Grand Ole Opry]]. A three-time [[Grammy Award for Best Male Country Vocal Performance|Grammy Award nominee]],<ref name=AP>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/country-musics-jack-greene-dies-nashville-164506536.html|title=Country music's Jack Greene dies in Nashville|publisher=Associated Press via Yahoo News website|accessdate=March 31, 2015}}</ref> Greene is best known for his 1966 hit, \"[[There Goes My Everything (song)|There Goes My Everything]]\". The song dominated the Country music charts for nearly two months in 1967 and earned Greene \"Male Vocalist of the Year\", \"Single of the Year\", \"Album of the Year\" and \"Song of the Year\" honors from the [[Country Music Association Awards|Country Music Association]].<ref name=AP/><ref name=Opry/> Greene had a total of five {{abbr|No.|number}}&nbsp;1 country hits and three others that reached the top ten. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' magazine named Greene one of the Top 100 \"Most Played Artists\".<ref name=Greene/>\n\n==Early career==\nGreene was born in [[Maryville, Tennessee]] and learned to play guitar when he was ten years old.<ref name=Opry>{{cite web|title=Jack Green  biodata|url=http://www.opry.com/artists/g/Greene_Jack.html|publisher=Grand Ole Opry official website|year=2013|accessdate=March 31, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413154304/https://www.opry.com/artists/g/Greene_Jack.html|archive-date=April 13, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> His first involvement with the music industry came when he was still a teenager, working as a [[disc jockey]] at radio station [[WGAP]] in Maryville.<ref name=AP/><ref name=Opry/>\n\nBy the age of 18, Greene was a regular on the ''Tennessee Barn Dance'' show on [[WNOX]] ([[Knoxville, Tennessee]]). In the early 1950s he moved to [[Atlanta, Georgia]], where he formed his own band, The Peach Tree Boys. Greene was lead [[vocalist]], [[drummer]], and [[guitarist]] for the group for eight years.<ref name=Greene/> In 1959, he moved back to Tennessee and settled in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] and formed another band, The Tennessee Mountain Boys. A major career break came Greene's way in 1961 when his band served as the opening act for [[Ernest Tubb]]. Impressed, Tubb asked Greene to become a part of his backing band, the Texas Troubadors in 1962.<ref name=Opry/>\n\nFor the next few years, Jack Greene was a drummer, guitarist, vocalist, and [[master of ceremonies]] for the Troubadors' performances. He soon began serving as opening act on a regular basis for Tubb, as well as playing in the band.<ref name=Opry/> In 1964, Jack released his first solo record with ''The Last Letter''. The song originally appeared on one of Ernest Tubb's live albums but drew enough attention that Tubb's record label, [[Decca Records]], released it as a single. Another single, \"Don't You Ever Get Tired (Of Hurting Me)\", followed in 1965 but failed to make the Country music charts, having the bad luck to come out at the same time as [[Ray Price (musician)|Ray Price]]'s version. Tubb encouraged Jack Greene to leave the Texas Troubadors and pursue a solo career. Said Greene in an interview, \"Ernest told me 'Son I believe it's time to go.' But also said 'If you can't make it you can always come back and be a Troubador'.\"<ref name=Opry/>\n\nGreene's first Top 40 hit came in early 1966 with \"Ever Since My Baby Went Away\", peaking at No.&nbsp;37. Later that year, Decca released what would become his signature song, \"There Goes My Everything\". The song reached No.&nbsp;1 and stayed on top of the country charts for 7 weeks while becoming a crossover hit. His success continued into 1967 with another No.&nbsp;1 in \"All The Time\" (on top for 5 weeks) and a number 2 hit with \"What Locks The Door\". In 1967, he received the prestigious awards for Male Vocalist of the Year, Single of the Year, and Album of the Year from the [[Country Music Association]]. In all, he recorded nine No.&nbsp;1 country hits on various charts including five No.&nbsp;1 ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' hits. His success continued into 1968 with another No.&nbsp;1 with \"[[You Are My Treasure]]\" and the top 5 hit \"Love Takes Care Of Me\".{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nIn 1969, he had two No.&nbsp;1 hits with \"[[Until My Dreams Come True]]\" and \"[[Statue of a Fool]]\". He completed the year out with the Top 5 \"Back In The Arms Of Love\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Roland|first=Tom|title=All Music Guide to CountryCountry'', 2nd ed.|location=San Francisco|publisher=[[Backbeat Books]]|year=2003|isbn=0-87930-760-9}}</ref> It was also in 1967 that Jack Greene became a member of the Grand Ole Opry.<ref name=Billboard2/> He became an Opry mainstay, performing there frequently each year until his health failed.\n\n==Later career==\nIn 1970, Greene gained a duet and a touring partner in [[Jeannie Seely]]. Together they had three Country hits including \"Wish I Didn't Have To Miss You\", which reached No.&nbsp;2 on the charts and became Greene's last top-ten hit.<ref name=Billboard2>{{cite web|last=Dauphin|first=Chuck|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-615/1552303/country-star-jack-greene-dead-at-83|title=Country Star Jack Greene Dead At 83|publisher=Billboard Magazine via official website|accessdate=March 31, 2015}}</ref> Jack and Jeannie's stage show became one of the biggest touring acts during the 1970s. Jack continued to have both solo hits and duets with Seely. Among the biggest of these hits during the 1970s included \"Lord, Is That Me\" (1970), \"There's A Lot About A Woman A Man Don't Know\" (1971), and two more duets with Jeannie with \"Much Obliged\" (1972) and \"What In The World Has Gone Wrong With Our Love\" (1972).<ref name=Greene/>\n\nDecca became [[MCA Records]] in the early 1970s but Greene kept on having chart success with \"Satisfaction\" (1973), \"I Need Somebody Bad\" (1973), and \"It's Time To Cross That Bridge\" (1974). Afterwards, his chart success declined rapidly as another song in 1974 and one song in 1975 were minor hits, and he was dropped by MCA Records in 1976.<ref name=Greene>{{cite web|title=Jack Greene's official website biography|url=http://www.jackgreeneopry.com/bio|year=2013|accessdate=March 16, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203015532/http://www.jackgreeneopry.com/bio/|archivedate=December 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\nJack Greene enjoyed a brief comeback with the [[Frontline Records]] label in 1980 as the song \"Yours For The Taking\" peaked at No.&nbsp;28 on the Country charts.<ref name=Billboard2/> The song would be Greene's last in the Country Top Forty. He achieved several more minor hits however on Frontline and then on EMH and [[Step One Records]]. He continued to tour regularly and appear on the Grand Ole Opry; 2007 marked his 40th anniversary with the Opry.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jack Green profile|url=http://www.opry.com/artists/g/Greene_Jack.html|publisher=Grand Ole Opry|accessdate=June 29, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190413154304/https://www.opry.com/artists/g/Greene_Jack.html|archive-date=April 13, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Opry Member List PDF |url=http://www.opry.com/img/Opry%20Members%20List.pdf |date=April 23, 2012 |accessdate=June 29, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120607030858/http://www.opry.com/img/Opry%20Members%20List.pdf |archivedate=June 7, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:JackandJollyGreenGiants2003.jpg|thumb|Jack & Jolly Green Giants 2003]]\n\n==Final years and death==\nGreene continued to record sporadically in the 2000s including the duet \"You Have Won My Heart\" and \"Stetson Cowboy\" with Santana Maria. However, it failed to chart. Greene recorded his final studio album ''Precious Memories, Treasured Friends'' in 2010. An album of duets, it featured fellow Country stars like [[Lorrie Morgan]] and [[George Jones]].<ref name=Billboard2/> In failing health, Greene retired from performing in 2011. He died on March 14, 2013 from complications of [[Alzheimer's disease]] at the age of 83 in [[Nashville, Tennessee]].<ref name=AP/>\n\nOn June 25, 2019, ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' listed Jack Greene among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]].<ref name=\"Rosen2\">{{cite web |last1=Rosen |first1=Jody |title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* 1967 &mdash; Became a member of the [[Grand Ole Opry]]\n* 1967 &mdash; [[Country Music Association]] - Male Vocalist of the Year\n* 1967 &mdash; Country Music Association - Single of the Year\n* 1967 &mdash; Country Music Association - Album of the Year\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n! colspan=\"2\"| Chart Positions\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Label\n|-\n! width=\"50\"| <small>[[Top Country Albums|US Country]]</small>\n! width=\"50\"| <small>[[Billboard 200|US]]</small>\n|-\n| 1966\n| ''There Goes My Everything''\n| align=\"center\"| 1\n| align=\"center\"| 66\n| rowspan=\"15\"| Decca\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1967\n| ''All the Time''\n| align=\"center\"| 1\n| align=\"center\"| 151\n|-\n| ''What Locks the Door''\n| align=\"center\"| 3\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1968\n| ''You Are My Treasure''\n| align=\"center\"| 5\n| \n|-\n| ''Love Takes Care of Me''\n| al